How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies were also offering trips to the West at the time, but one had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the night like this, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to the "politically unreliable people," who could not travel at all.
Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czechs' way of travelling has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us he was the only one going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that Croatia's current favourite destination, until 1989 could not be travelled freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take with them the food (conservatives, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and so did average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With increased demand for travel agencies began, starting in 1997, regularly, to prepare for travel using charter flight connections, which led to an incredible drop in travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs were already travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries depart every year. This winter will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15 thousand CZK per head on overseas trips, including expenses on the stay site.
