"I am a military commander in the Norwegian resistance movement and in the Templar Knights of Norway," he said in front of a room full of 500 people.
"I am opposed to the court, as it was mandated by organizations that support the ideology of hatred and because it supports multiculturalism."
"I recognize the facts but I do not plead guilty."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during that monologue, because "he did not want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this hearing as a platform for him to express his views."
For the same reason he refused to allow Breivik, who brought a speech written in advance, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered the police to keep Breivik in custody for 12 more weeks, banned him from access to the media for four weeks, and said the authorities would have to have strict control over all visits and correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 survivors and relatives of the victims attended the hearing.
Some came in the hope of looking Breivik in the eye, others to confirm that he is locked up.
They all attended with the aim of moving towards completion.
"I thought it looked cold and inhuman," a Utoya survivor told Norwegian radio station NRK.
"It was awkward, but for me it was a step forward after seeing and hearing the suspect."
Dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the audience and looked the journalists and survivors in the eye when he entered and left the building.
Despite Breivik's strange notion of being part of a major "resistance" movement, the judge determined that he is not a mentally ill, and said there is no evidence that he acted with accomplices.
Some may be comforted that the July 22 attacks appear to be the work of an extremist rather than a group of radicals.
But that does not automatically soften the pain and confusion that an entire nation still feels.
"I'd like it to look like a monster, but it doesn't look like it," said a relative of a victim.
"It'd be a lot easier if it seemed like it."
7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Shown in a Theater This Week
Following the death of Steve Jobs, on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview with Jobs recently rediscovered which has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in the larger markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a designer, dreamer and self-recognised hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a junkie of flowcharts - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease consisting of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he already worked intensely at his new computer company NeXT, awaiting popular Internet adoption.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy was discovered at VHS in the director's garage.
This archival material, slightly reissued, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technology philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster towards the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs that we see here, the eager dreamer on the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers that they invariably give you are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs brings your efforts to simplify Apple's accounting in detail.
Disconcerted by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of a good cubier, and then adjusted with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and shouting through the pay phone and returning a minute later to the pay phone next door," Jobs says with a giggle.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - it was an amazing lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling it over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute telephone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
He was as big as a suitcase, he had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with him.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of motherboards, a customer asked him if he could assemble the entire team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, he had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and left and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's revival, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble into their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, so what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could've been ten times its size, it could've been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
Much is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make electrons do, glass makes them, robots make them, factories make them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything is reduced to taste - it is reduced to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has ever done, and then trying to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been embarrassed about stealing big ideas.
What made the Macintosh big in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who by chance were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health care law rivals while the court accepts the case
The day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to discuss the politically controversial issue of whether they would accept President Obama's health care law challenge, two of its judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were given at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will present the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met at a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a war cry for conservative activists across the country.
The judges agreed to accept the lawsuit and, in fact, a historic plea of five and a half hours is expected by March, and the outcome will likely further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court's decision becomes known.
The lawyer who will appear before the court and claim that the law must be dismissed will probably be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has long been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another signature that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
Dinner was held in a Washington hotel, hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees were, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most important Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the healthcare law.
Special guests at dinner? Mm-hmm. Scalia and Thomas.
It's nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal magistrates.
If they were not, it could be said that they would fall under the Canon 4C Code, which states: "A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related organizations and others, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or be on the agenda of such an event. "
However, the absolute proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as to a company with enormous financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
"This impressive gap in ethics and indifference to the code goes against the demands of several magistrates who abide by the same rules that apply to all federal judges," said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause.
"The judges were entertained in a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending before the court."
Their appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say they mix the court's activity too easily with the agenda driven by groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Judge Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the attorney general of the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
His critics have pressured Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has not given any indication that he will.
