"The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department," Panetta said in a letter to Arizona Republican Senators John McCain and South Carolina Republican Lindsey Graham.
He said Congress' failure to reach agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "kidnapping," would result in 23 percent overall reductions and a halt to many new projects.
"A cut so large, applied in this indiscriminate manner, would make most of our shipbuilding and construction projects impossible to execute - you cannot buy three quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously damage other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We would also be forced to remove many of our civilian officials inadvertently and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to discharge civilians in order to meet the target."
"These changes would break the faith with those who maintain our army and seriously damage the good disposition."
The cuts over time would reach the combat troops, Panetta said.
"While wartime funding in overseas contingency operations accounts is not directly affected by kidnapping, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disruptions in base budgets," Panetta warned.
"The recruitment of staff would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of the contract that supports the war."
"The payroll staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and legal and political support would be interrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information on the possible impact of automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would cause a rapid decline of the United States as the world's leading military power."
"We are firmly against this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
"This is not a result with which one can live, and it is certainly not one that we should impose ourselves."
"Hijacking is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it must not be allowed to happen."
Whether Panetta's letter and recent senators' warnings will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly frank about possible cuts, even though she came to work at the top of the Pentagon with years of budget experience in Congress and the White House and knowing that she was facing difficult decisions.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what might be ahead - an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots."
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough soldiers trained to accomplish the mission," Panetta said in her opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries."
"Indeed, he invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta sets out new details of how reductions "generate significant operational risks: delay in response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be deployed and previously engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations."
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter fighter aircraft, a planned new bomber, the new generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship and the new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping the development and additional testing of the F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is the next vital step in improving and addressing potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone stating to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
Surely, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
Liars do look in the eye.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush, or get restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "oriented towards others" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than people who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called creating a baseline.
Helps to provide benchmarks for later measurement of changes.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
You'd better know if someone normally bangs on the foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavior groups as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember its history, can point their feet toward the door, lean toward a way out, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely show that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used past time as he claimed his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
