Climate adversity stopped the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's administration, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, reduced foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled of change, that generated high expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost affects, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was sustained in 582,835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops being those of vegetables, maize and chickpea.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55,053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in number of people leaves more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first semester of 18,969 individuals.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a resource restriction by legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who illegally grab dollars it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and secondly because entering they already have many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being contributing as a worker to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor lags are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Combined with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the biggest decline in direct foreign investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June of the state FDI totaled 630,697 dollars, representing a drop of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143,312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the state government asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reviving the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government shows a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he lacked the harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the terrain that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, it failed to align the effort of all and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts of the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, he said that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resource be detonated," he said.
Work to be done
The president of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better directs the government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the government has been trying to achieve good results in various areas, there is some progress in economic development, but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to say that the government is being more inclusive, what I can say is that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
