Valid "analogue blackout" cut in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog to digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes between the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue blackout" from 2021 to 2015, by not gathering the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be followed to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for failing to reach the eight-vote qualified majority for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and the decree remains in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and upon admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without going into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to be prepared.
"I also do not think that if I did this it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, who has the constitutional mandate, the governing body of the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, resulting in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitization, which implies a decision of public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance of the State, includes a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the executive, in issuing the contested decree, which in some way encroaches on the sphere of competence of Congress, as compliance with the laws issued by the legislature is being provided in the administrative sphere, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data provided by the PREP, the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local norms with federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the current electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines provided for in the Official State Newspaper Law, on the grounds that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislature and called the state president's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal," since he has no right to "sanction or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to make partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may occur in the event that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of counting and counting in the box file or it does not work in the hands of the president of the box; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the ballot received in all polling stations may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the presumed candidate winning the election concerned and the candidate obtaining the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the party and/or coalition representative who ran for the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the vote may also be made if, at the end of the ordinary count, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the second candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was placed second, in which case electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation there is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
