This was the work of the caleño who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Cali lophoscopist went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a CTI lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top Farc chief: "Alfonso Cano", through the collation of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the STI section, Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years, was on "availability" that week.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to spend more than five days in the jungle to get to the place where the bodies had to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after completing the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of the frictional skin, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar he was warned to wear minimum clothing for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry the decadactillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local peasant, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the defense minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the FARC.
In search of the footprint
For a Sijín de Cali dactyloscopist, the recognition given by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin of error, that can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, the lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the persons captured.
When captured, many criminals present false cards or have no papers.
We took their fingerprints and looked them up in the database.
The researcher said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the criminal, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Prints can also rule out or reassert suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the crime scene.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that in objects "the footprints are extracted with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the STI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the television show CSI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective comparison is performed.
