And, despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Québec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report had reached conclusions that did not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which had already stated that it did not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians, pro-euthanasia
Let us remember that 85 per cent of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, as they believe that it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of the elderly or disabled have less value.
With regard to persons who had committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents were of the opinion that proceedings should not be initiated against them.
With regard to the maintenance or interruption of a patient's health care, the situation is not so clear, as the authors of the report indicate.
Furthermore, among its recommendations, it suggests that the Criminal Code should indicate that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also calls for training of health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls on governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in health institutions in Canada, the committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be regarded as euthanasia and be subjected to the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations regarding the findings of the report of the Royal Society of Canada experts.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of experts who sign the report as "extreme", among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and over 18 years of age can ask for help to commit suicide," says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she described as "manifesting in favour of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, questions especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
