Energy policy:
facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is appropriate for an electoral meeting to be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The discussion would be useful only if it considered the full economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, not forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case with Belgium, which subjects its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor with Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite a few examples, are continuing with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power station interrupted after the crash of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
The choice of Berlin will lead to an increase in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
Consideration should be given to the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which he obtains 30% of his electricity, is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittance of the wind; for this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract realistically from the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, they do not object in principle to this type of energy, according to surveys.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost construction of an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create non-localizable jobs.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear power, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva's development of low-CO2 and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a safety authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not have consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While being studied by all the electrical actors who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to Areva and EDF's competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a debate that is so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France's "human rights country".
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande merely includes banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may prove to be electorally profitable, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restriction of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pushing for lower wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly employed in sectors with no employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and those that are more skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country lacking anesthesiologists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the salaries and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that an increase of 1% in migration flows represents an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized US Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 years will make a net contribution (income less expenditure) of 150,000 euros to average public budgets throughout his or her life.
At the beginning of his tenure, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to vote as directly as possible.
We know, from Napoleon "the Little One", that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a twofold revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected upon in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a halt to the vacuum of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take any action, but a common, full-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to finish the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is folded to the orders of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from their impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers a humiliation at the international level.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
What is most urgent is that popular sovereignty should regain the helm of the European project.
Because it is only together that Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investment.
A solution to the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having long fought against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead to a new deadlock.
We must take on a new stage in European integration.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The Interest-Motivated Revolution would not be enough.
This lesson remains applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
Only by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European people's sovereignty, can it be achieved.
To build Europe, let us become Europeans.
"Contactless" chip cards are generalised
The world chip card show starts Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which allows you to pay for common transport or purchases simply by bringing the card to a reader.
This year, 460 million non-contact chip cards will be sold worldwide, $320 million more than the previous year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (a projected 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the world market for chip cards (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa cards are being used without contact.
But the large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million non-contact Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To get the upper gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
"There are two major French establishments that have committed themselves to systematically disseminating contactless bank cards to their customers in the future," announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile phone payment
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
At present, there are few devices equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is indispensable for conducting transactions.
"They're falling behind."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units in 2012 worldwide," explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Crédit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a cover that allows payment without contact.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseilles.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile phone.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the long suspected Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Mesahel, even stated that Algiers already "has the certainty".
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports demonstrate that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to reach a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the runways.
Raptured in a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates a number of interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues particularly attracted the interest of the investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in Boko Haram's evolution and discourses or in his operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since pressured Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened little worthy of interest.
Fast success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for the sharia, while its militants throw themselves into the fight against the unholy central government.
The latter focus primarily on churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, United Nations local headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, ranging from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is a matter of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and stated that he was willing to "share all the information".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
In relation to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
Can an America weakened by crisis manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might think so.
For a few days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have increasingly made loud and short-cut statements on foreign policy, traditionally a strong point for Republicans.
The slogans, often unfounded, spread over China, Iran, aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate in the race for the Grand Old Party nomination, has threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them "for manipulating their currency", a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of their sector to Asia.
It doesn't matter if that involves the explosion of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, the former Obama Ambassador to China and the only candidate who has a sophisticated vision of foreign policy, almost chokes on an attitude that "flashes" emotions.
He called for a strong, but constructive, dialogue with Beijing (Obama's current position).
But Huntsman, who is stuck in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Reagan-style
Romney has also promised a military intervention in Iran if the sanctions fail to disrupt his nuclear program.
"If I get elected, I will stop Iran," he boasted.
"If Obama gets re-elected, they'll have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of having failed his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-ranked candidate, shows shameful ignorance of such issues.
Recently, he urged to counter the Chinese military threat because Beijing "attempts to develop nuclear capability", apparently ignoring the fact that China already has the military atom since 1964.
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to intervene in Iran, says he is willing to deploy the U.S. military to Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
The differences are considerable with the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
The current President's opponents answer that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They remember that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to loosen the piston in the fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of their naive dialogue with Iran, the hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq and their misrepresentations in Libya, and label it as weak.
But the attacks are not easy for them.
The people judge Obama's national security balance, which ended with Bin Laden, in a rather positive way.
From Iraq, he distrusts the military interventions that lead to a sinking.
And, arguing that America needs to be economically rebuilt to resurrect its leadership, Obama seems to be more just.
The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic coast, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and their Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, each year an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 to provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous play presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, preventing the passage of land by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening it with closing access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us," François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are as political as well as economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from anchors on ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream society.
It was also necessary to strengthen measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its full length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project renounced it when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state company to establish itself permanently at sea off its coast.
"In case of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," Jens Müller says.
In the event of leakage, gas from the gas pipeline shall therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have foreseen joints that, according to forecasts, they will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
To it, the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for a period of 25 years renewable, the totality of the gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," Jens Müller says.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline has been carried out by 30 per cent with the contribution of shareholders and 70 per cent through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone takes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has remained a long way off.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The Italian small business, which had twelve workers at its inception, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with Moleskine's development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be mentioned that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous barriers to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not completed their baccalaureate and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with an average of 38 per cent.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that "constitute the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapin, General Manager of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality progresses, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité pointed out that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually deficient".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6 per cent of disabled workers, a target that was set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3 per cent," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created a great deal of pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of companies with 100 to 199 workers.
Hazard: "A Joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20h45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure of this friendly match.
We will not dare to say that there was collusion among them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side, on the stand of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made amends.
Five months after his striker's spiteful gesture against Turkey, the Belgian picker has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and for being Belgian."
"I want to move forward," Lille's striker replies.
As for the contrast between his presentations in his team and in the selection, "it's a set", has been justified.
"In Lille, I'm here all year, which doesn't apply to Belgium.
"I have to place myself."
Called to play against Romania on Friday night, considering this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "shield".
Not forgetting the "pleasure."
He has been encouraging the Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been his fan," he says.
This will certainly particularly reinforce the "particular" character of the meeting.
Especially because he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami)," he recalls.
"We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
With simplicity, Leekens has made reference to "pride".
"Pride" for contesting "a gala match".
"Pride" also for checking, as "neighbor", that France "returns to a very high level team", about a year after Knysna's trauma.
"Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job," he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the technician would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Bleus towards... Brazil, in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing," he said.
"We're building something; the players are ambitious, they're hungry.
"You'll be able to see it in the next games." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal is facing with great optimism the party back against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the one-way match, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes pass, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Selecçao, which he has run since September 2010, will qualify for the 2012 Euro.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a game to play and a rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Considering the one-way match (0-0), Friday in Zenica's hell, it seems obvious that the thing is not decided.
Portugal dominated the match for more than an hour, yes, but could not score the valuable goal that would have given it the tranquility.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't marked out of the house."
But at home, in the bright Lisbon Light Stadium, the Portuguese are convinced that they will pass, before an audience that should be just as excited, even if it is evident that the party "is very equal", dixit an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the match is very close, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance to participate in the Euro 2012", said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
Bosnians could get a draw, though they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't marked out of the house," Bento laments.
"We are going to play against a team that has a high technical quality and has players with a high individual quality," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting, from the beginning, maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "not leave them time to think".
A good idea, as long as, this time, it's realistic.
